      "body" : "@red888 The <code>build</code> builds regular ones while <code>testClasses</code> build test ones. You can check the different tasks here <a href=\"https://docs.gradle.org/current/userguide/java_plugin.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">docs.gradle.org/current/userguide/java_plugin.html</a>"
    } ],
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 365271,
      "reputation" : 31168,
      "user_id" : 710099,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 79,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0413774874b9baeccef7a5ba0344fec7?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Federico Piazza",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/710099/federico-piazza"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 42,
    "last_activity_date" : 1649412152,
    "last_edit_date" : 1649412152,
    "creation_date" : 1583258269,
    "answer_id" : 60513086,
    "question_id" : 4597850,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>Using <code>-x test</code> skip test execution but this also exclude test code compilation.</p>\n<pre><code>gradle build -x test \n</code></pre>\n<p>In our case, we have a CI/CD process where one goal is compilation and next goal is testing (Build -&gt; Test).</p>\n<p>So, for our first <code>Build</code> goal we wanted to ensure that the whole project compiles well. For this we have used:</p>\n<pre><code>./gradlew build testClasses -x test\n</code></pre>\n<p>On the next goal we simply execute tests:</p>\n<pre><code>./gradlew test\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 6445011,
      "reputation" : 954,
      "user_id" : 6197874,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://graph.facebook.com/10209638129455241/picture?type=large",
      "display_name" : "Arnau Sistach Reinoso",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/6197874/arnau-sistach-reinoso"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 5,
    "last_activity_date" : 1584431710,
    "creation_date" : 1584431710,
    "answer_id" : 60718284,
    "question_id" : 4597850,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>In <a href=\"https://docs.gradle.org/current/userguide/java_plugin.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\">The Java Plugin</a>:</p>\n\n<pre><code>$ gradle tasks\n\nBuild tasks\n-----------\nassemble - Assembles the outputs of this project.\nbuild - Assembles and tests this project.\ntestClasses - Assembles test classes.\n\nVerification tasks\n------------------\ntest - Runs the unit tests.\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Gradle build without test you have two options:</p>\n\n<pre><code>$ gradle assemble\n$ gradle build -x test\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>but if you want compile test:</p>\n\n<pre><code>$ gradle assemble testClasses\n$ gradle testClasses\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 1575780,
      "reputation" : 11874,
      "user_id" : 1462282,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 100,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/5wvoe.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Sahil Chhabra",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1462282/sahil-chhabra"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 25,
    "last_activity_date" : 1597047412,
    "creation_date" : 1597047412,
    "answer_id" : 63336500,
    "question_id" : 4597850,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>Every action in gradle is a <code>task</code>, and so is <code>test</code>. And to exclude a <code>task</code> from gradle run, you can use the option <code>--exclude-task</code> or it's shorthand <code>-x</code> followed by the task name which needs to be excluded. Example:</p>\n<pre><code>gradle build -x test\n</code></pre>\n<p>The <code>-x</code> option should be repeated for all the tasks that needs to be excluded.</p>\n<p>If you have different tasks for different type of tests in your <code>build.gradle</code> file, then you need to skip all those tasks that executes test. Say you have a task <code>test</code> which executes unit-tests and a task <code>testFunctional</code> which executes functional-tests. In this case, you can exclude all tests like below:</p>\n<pre><code>gradle build -x test -x testFunctional\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 11726648,
      "reputation" : 26351,
      "user_id" : 8583692,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/joGZ9.png?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Mahozad",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/8583692/mahozad"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 1,
    "last_activity_date" : 1702125635,
    "creation_date" : 1702125635,
    "answer_id" : 77631292,
    "question_id" : 4597850,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>This is a solution for Kotlin DSL (build.gradle.<strong>kts</strong>):</p>\n<pre class=\"lang-kotlin prettyprint-override\"><code>tasks.withType&lt;Test&gt; { // OR tasks.test {\n    onlyIf {\n        properties[&quot;areTestsEnabled&quot;].toString().toBoolean()\n    }\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p>Execute the build like this:</p>\n<pre class=\"lang-bash prettyprint-override\"><code>./gradlew build\n</code></pre>\n<p>To include running tests:</p>\n<pre class=\"lang-bash prettyprint-override\"><code>./gradlew build -PareTestsEnabled=true\n</code></pre>\n"
  } ],
